"""
MKT Context Commentary — Ephesians chapters 5–6
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-ephesians-5-6.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/ephesians.json
- data/translation/glossary-greek.json (σάρξ disp=4, πνεῦμα disp=3, δικαιοσύνη disp=4, ἀγάπη disp=3)
- data/translation/notes/ephesians.json (dispute flags, token analysis)
- data/translation/draft/mediating/ephesians.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/ellicott/ephesians.json (verse-level background)

Key decisions in this range:
- Household code (Haustafeln) treated as a recognizable Greco-Roman literary form that Paul
  subverts with a Christological center, not merely imports
- "Principalities and powers" (archai/exousiai) treated as Second Temple Jewish cosmology —
  real spiritual agents over nations, not only metaphors for human institutions
- The "ambassador in chains" (6:20) read against ancient diplomatic immunity conventions;
  Paul's paradox is deliberate
- Armor of God allusions to Isa 59:17 and Wis 5:17-20 noted throughout
- 5:14 hymn fragment treated as an early Christian baptismal hymn, not a direct OT quote
  (the common scholarly consensus; OT echoes noted but not over-identified)
- "Fear/reverence" (phobeomai 5:33) translated as respectful honor, not terror
- Tychicus identified as Asia-province delegate known from Acts 20:4 and Col 4:7
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html


EPHESIANS = {
  "5": {
    "1": '<p>The command to be <em>imitators of God</em> (<em>mimētai tou theou</em>) is unique in the NT and striking against the Greco-Roman background. Greek and Roman writers did speak of imitating the gods, but the gods of Homer and Hesiod modeled deception, rivalry, and lust — traits Paul explicitly forbids in the preceding chapters. The Jewish critique of pagan religion was precisely that its gods were immoral. Paul inverts the frame: God himself is the pattern because he is love and light, not because he is powerful. The "dear children" (tekna agapēta) framing activates kinship language; in the ancient Mediterranean, family resemblance was a social and moral category — children were expected to replicate the character of their father.</p>',

    "2": '<p>"Walk in the way of love" picks up the OT walk-language of covenant faithfulness (<em>halakh</em>), familiar to any synagogue-background reader. The description of Christ\'s self-offering as "a fragrant offering and sacrifice" (<em>osmē euōdias</em>, <em>prosphora kai thusia</em>) is direct cultic language from the Septuagint — the formula appears dozens of times in Leviticus and Numbers for burnt offerings pleasing to the LORD. Paul applies the entire sacrificial register to Christ\'s death, signaling that the temple cult\'s purpose is fulfilled. The original audience, whether Jewish or God-fearing Gentile, would have recognized the priestly register at once.</p>',

    "3": '<p>Ephesus was among the most significant commercial and religious centers of the ancient world, home to the temple of Artemis — one of the Seven Wonders. The city had a significant sex trade connected to its port economy and to cult practices at various temples. Sexual immorality (<em>porneia</em>) and impurity (<em>akatharsia</em>) were not merely personal failings in this context; they were woven into civic and religious life. Paul\'s call for these things not to be "even named among you" invokes the Jewish concept of separation from defilement (<em>havdalah</em>) — the holy people maintain a boundary that defines them over against their environment. The identification of covetousness as a form of idolatry was a standard move in Hellenistic Jewish ethics (Philo, Josephus), naming wealth-acquisition as a rival loyalty to God.</p>',

    "4": '<p>"Foolish talk" (<em>mōrologia</em>) and "coarse joking" (<em>eutrapelia</em>) were recognized categories in Hellenistic moral discourse. Notably, Aristotle in the Nicomachean Ethics praised <em>eutrapelia</em> as a social virtue — the ability to joke with wit and propriety. Paul is not condemning all humor but the degraded form that traffics in obscenity. "Filthiness" (<em>aischrotēs</em>) was a standard rhetorical term for shameful conduct. The contrast — "rather, thanksgiving" — echoes the Hellenistic symposium convention, where gratitude to the host was the proper table-manner. Paul redirects the entire category of social speech toward eucharistia.</p>',

    "5": '<p>The catalogue of those who have "no inheritance in the kingdom" (5:5) follows a Second Temple Jewish tradition of excluding the immoral from the age to come, seen in texts like 1 Corinthians 6:9–10, 1 Enoch, and the Dead Sea Scrolls. The Qumran community maintained explicit lists of those disqualified from their assembly. The equivalence "greedy person = idolater" reflects Jewish wisdom: covetousness was treated as the worship of wealth rather than God (cf. Matt 6:24). The phrase "kingdom of Christ and of God" is theologically unusual — Paul typically speaks of "God\'s kingdom" — suggesting an identity of Christ\'s reign with God\'s own.</p>',

    "6": '<p>"Empty words" (<em>kenois logois</em>) likely targets antinomian teaching circulating in Ephesus — possibly an early form of the view that spiritual status is independent of moral behavior. This proto-gnostic position (full development came in the 2nd century) held that the spiritual self was unaffected by bodily actions. Paul counters that God\'s wrath comes precisely because of "these things." The phrase "children of disobedience" (<em>huioi tēs apeithias</em>) is a Semitic construction: "sons of X" means those defined by X as their essential quality. This is Hebraism adapted into Greek, familiar from Qumran texts ("sons of darkness") and the Synoptic Gospels.</p>',

    "7": '<p>The brevity of this verse is deliberate — Paul simply restates the boundary: do not share in their practices. The Greco-Roman world operated on patronage and social networks where participation in others\' religious and social activities was nearly unavoidable. Paul\'s instruction cuts against the grain of social obligation; not sharing in the practices of immoral companions was a countercultural stance that would have cost social capital.</p>',

    "8": '<p>The light/darkness dualism Paul invokes here has deep roots in Second Temple Jewish thought. The Community Rule (1QS) from Qumran divides humanity into "sons of light" and "sons of darkness" under the authority of the Prince of Light and the Angel of Darkness respectively. The War Scroll (1QM) envisions a final cosmic battle between these two camps. Paul\'s formulation is sharper than mere metaphor: "you were darkness" — not merely "in darkness" — identifies the whole person with the domain of darkness before conversion. The transfer to the domain of light is a change of identity, not just environment.</p>',

    "9": '<p>Ellicott\'s observation is important: the best-attested reading is "fruit of the light," not "fruit of the Spirit" (which appears in some manuscripts, likely harmonizing with Gal 5:22). The triad "goodness, righteousness, truth" (<em>agathōsynē, dikaiosynē, alētheia</em>) maps onto Hellenistic virtue categories while being grounded in OT categories of covenant faithfulness. <em>Dikaiosynē</em> here is moral uprightness, not forensic justification — context determines its meaning, and in a list of character qualities it carries the ethical sense. The disputed term (disp=4) is handled by MKT as "righteousness" following the ethical reading.</p>',

    "10": '<p>"Finding out what pleases the Lord" (<em>dokimazō</em>) draws on the Hellenistic practice of testing coins or metals for purity — <em>dokimazō</em> was used for assaying gold. The Stoic moral tradition also used the concept of testing actions against the rational standard. Paul redirects the standard: not reason alone, but what is "acceptable to the Lord" (<em>euareston tō kyriō</em>). This phrase echoes Hellenistic Jewish usage in Philo and the Wisdom of Solomon, where pleasing God was the criterion for ethical decision-making.</p>',

    "11": '<p>"Have nothing to do with the fruitless deeds of darkness, but rather expose them" (<em>elegchō</em>) — the verb carries a legal and public dimension in Greek usage: to reprove, convict, or bring to light in a judicial sense. It is used in contexts of formal accusation and public rebuke. This goes beyond personal avoidance; the community is to actively bring the deeds of darkness into the light of public exposure. In the ancient city, shame and honor were publicly enforced; bringing shameful conduct to light was itself a social sanction.</p>',

    "12": '<p>The secrecy of certain pagan worship was part of its self-presentation as elite mystery knowledge — the mystery cults of Eleusis, Isis, and Mithras all involved secret rites whose content initiates were forbidden to disclose. Paul identifies the secrecy itself as evidence of shame: things that must be hidden are things whose nature cannot bear public scrutiny. The contrast with Christian practice (which Paul urges to "expose") is pointed.</p>',

    "13": '<p>The logic here exploits the Greek understanding of light as the agent of revealing: in the physical world, objects become visible only when light falls on them; what is in darkness is invisible. Paul applies this to moral reality: the Christian community\'s life of goodness, righteousness, and truth functions as a kind of ambient light that renders hidden practices visible by contrast. This is a practical mechanism of cultural witness, not only a spiritual metaphor.</p>',

    "14": '<p>The citation formula "it is said" (<em>legei</em>) without an OT reference suggests Paul is quoting something other than Scripture — most likely an early Christian hymn, possibly used at baptism. The content echoes Isaiah 26:19 ("your dead will live") and Isaiah 60:1 ("Arise, shine, for your light has come"), but it is not an exact quotation of either. The early church regularly composed hymns that wove together scriptural themes (cf. Phil 2:6–11; Col 1:15–20). The address "sleeper" and "rise from the dead" maps onto the baptismal narrative: the candidate descends into the water (death) and rises to new life, and Christ shines on them as their new reality.</p>',

    "15": '<p>The exhortation to "walk carefully" (<em>akribōs</em>) as the wise, not as fools, draws on the Jewish "two ways" tradition prominent in Proverbs 1–9, Psalm 1, and Deuteronomic literature: there is a way of life and a way of death, wisdom and folly, and the fundamental orientation of one\'s whole life is at stake in the choice. In Second Temple literature this framework is developed extensively in the Wisdom of Solomon and Sirach. The Didache (early 2nd century) opens with exactly this structure, suggesting it was a standard catechetical framework. Paul invokes it here with eschatological urgency.</p>',

    "16": '<p>"Making the most of every opportunity" (<em>exagorazomenoi ton kairon</em>) uses the market term <em>exagorazō</em> ("buy up") applied to <em>kairos</em> — the opportune moment as distinct from <em>chronos</em> (clock time). In Hellenistic rhetoric, kairos was the decisive moment that required the prepared speaker or actor; Ecclesiastes uses a similar concept (3:1–8, "a time for everything"). Paul combines this with apocalyptic urgency: "because the days are evil" signals that the present age is under hostile occupation and the opportunities for good are limited. The same phrase appears in Colossians 4:5, suggesting it was Paul\'s standard formulation.</p>',

    "17": '<p>"Do not be foolish" (<em>aphron</em>) is stronger than the "unwise" of verse 15; <em>aphron</em> appears in the LXX for those who deny God (Ps 14:1) and in Luke\'s parables for the man who builds barns without reference to God (Luke 12:20). Understanding "what the Lord\'s will is" (<em>thelēma tou kyriou</em>) is the defining mark of the wise person in Pauline ethics. The Stoic tradition located wisdom in understanding the logos/rational order; Paul locates it in the personal will of the Lord, which requires revelation and relationship rather than philosophical reasoning alone.</p>',

    "18": '<p>The contrast between wine and Spirit directly addresses the ecstatic religious practices of Ephesus. The Dionysiac cult (worship of Dionysus/Bacchus, god of wine) involved ritual drunkenness as a means of divine possession; the <em>thiasoi</em> (cultic associations) were common in Ephesian civic life, and drunken ecstasy was considered a form of divine encounter. Paul does not deny that drunkenness produces altered states; he denies that these states represent authentic encounter with God, contrasting them with genuine Spirit-filling. The Acts narrative hints at this when Pentecost observers mistake Spirit-filling for wine (Acts 2:13).</p>',

    "19": '<p>The three categories — "psalms, hymns, and spiritual songs" (<em>psalmoi, hymnoi, ōdai pneumatikai</em>) — likely reflect distinct forms of early Christian worship. Psalms were probably the biblical Psalter, foundational to Jewish worship in synagogue and home. Hymns were composed pieces of praise, possibly including the Christ-hymns embedded in Paul\'s letters (Phil 2:6–11; Col 1:15–20). "Spiritual songs" (<em>ōdai pneumatikai</em>) likely refers to spontaneous Spirit-inspired utterance, the sung equivalent of tongues. The Qumran community also composed original hymns (the Hodayot scroll) alongside the biblical Psalms, suggesting this dual practice was not entirely novel.</p>',

    "20": '<p>The call to "give thanks always for everything" (<em>eucharistountes pantote hyper pantōn</em>) appropriates the language of <em>eucharistia</em> — a term loaded with social obligation in the Hellenistic world. In patron-client relationships, gratitude (<em>charis</em> given, <em>eucharistia</em> returned) was the binding social currency; failing to give thanks to a patron was a serious breach. Paul universalizes this as the posture of the Christian toward God as ultimate patron and Father. The theological move is significant: all goods come from God (not from human patrons), so gratitude runs vertically rather than horizontally.</p>',

    "21": '<p>This verse is the structural hinge of the household code section. In the Greco-Roman household (<em>oikos</em>), the hierarchy was assumed and legally encoded: the Roman <em>patria potestas</em> gave the father legal authority over wife, children, and slaves. The Hellenistic household management tradition (Aristotle\'s Politics 1.1, Hellenistic Jewish writers like Philo and Josephus) treated the household as a microcosm of the state. Paul\'s insertion of "submitting to one another" (<em>hypotassomenoi allēlois</em>) before the specific household instructions frames the entire section under mutual subordination — a move that subverts the hierarchical logic even as the hierarchy is addressed. The motivation — "out of reverence for Christ" — displaces the social system\'s self-justifying logic.</p>',

    "22": '<p>Paul\'s instruction to wives to "submit to your own husbands as to the Lord" follows the Hellenistic household code form but with a crucial difference. In Aristotle\'s Politics and in standard Greco-Roman household management literature, the husband\'s authority was natural and self-justifying — wives were subordinate because of their nature. Paul\'s ground is Christological: the husband\'s headship is analogous to Christ\'s headship, which means it is defined by what Christ does in the following verses. The "own" (idios) applied to "husbands" limits the scope — this is not a general subordination of all women to all men, but of wives within the specific covenant of marriage.</p>',

    "23": '<p>The head-body metaphor for Christ and the church draws on Paul\'s earlier development in Ephesians 1:22–23 and 4:15–16. In 1 Corinthians 11:3 Paul also uses <em>kephalē</em> (head) of the husband-wife relationship, though there he links it to creation order. The term <em>kephalē</em> in Greek carried connotations of authority and leadership; the claim that it meant only "source" (as in some modern interpretations) is philologically contested. More significant here is Paul\'s addition of "the Savior of the body" — the husband\'s headship is defined by analogy with a Savior who gave himself sacrificially. The definition of leadership as salvation rather than dominion is Paul\'s distinctive contribution.</p>',

    "24": '<p>The qualification "in everything" (<em>en panti</em>) would have been heard against the backdrop of Roman household law, where a husband\'s authority was near-absolute. Paul invokes the church-Christ analogy as the regulating principle: as the church submits to Christ, so wives to husbands. But the analogy cuts both ways — the entire following section defines what Christ actually does for the church, which then defines what the husband is obligated to be. The "everything" is constrained by what Christ-like headship actually requires.</p>',

    "25": '<p>"Husbands, love your wives, just as Christ loved the church and gave himself up for her" — the comparison is extraordinary by any ancient standard. Greco-Roman moral philosophy did speak of husbands\' obligation to care for their wives, but the normative frame was beneficent authority, not self-sacrifice. The Stoic Musonius Rufus (roughly Paul\'s contemporary) argued for mutual fidelity in marriage as a philosophical position, but nothing in Hellenistic household ethics matched the command to love with the self-giving love of the Crucifixion as the standard. Paul has taken the form of the household code and loaded it with content that transforms its logic.</p>',

    "26": '<p>"Cleansing her by the washing with water through the word" (<em>loutron tou hydatos en rhēmati</em>) is widely understood as a reference to baptism. In early Christian practice, baptism was accompanied by a spoken word — either a baptismal formula, a creedal confession, or a proclamation of the gospel. The combination of water and word echoes Jewish purification practice (immersion in the mikveh) and also the Greek tradition of ritual washings before sacred events. The novelty is the identification of Christ as the one who performs the cleansing through the community\'s baptismal practice.</p>',

    "27": '<p>The image of presenting the bride is drawn from the ancient wedding ceremony. In Greek and Roman practice, a <em>paranymphos</em> (the equivalent of a best man) would escort the bride to the groom and formally present her. Paul applies this image to Christ, who presents the church to himself — in an unusual doubling, Christ is both the groom who receives the bride and the paranymphos who prepares her. The language of "without stain or wrinkle" (<em>mē echousa spilon ē rhytida</em>) echoes the inspection of a sacrificial animal for blemish and also the presentation of a bride as unblemished. The combination of sacrifice and marriage imagery is deliberate.</p>',

    "28": '<p>The care of one\'s own body was a well-established topic in Hellenistic ethics. The Stoics insisted on the duty of self-preservation as part of natural law; Epictetus distinguished between what is "up to us" (the soul) and our body, which we must maintain as a social responsibility. Paul uses this common-ground assumption — no one hates his own body — as a moral lever to argue for the husband\'s obligation to love his wife, since she is, in the analogy, part of his own body. The argument presupposes the "one flesh" union of marriage (Gen 2:24, quoted in v.31).</p>',

    "29": '<p>The two verbs "nourish" (<em>ektrefō</em>) and "cherish" (<em>thalpō</em>) describe aspects of bodily care. <em>Ektrefō</em> was used for raising children to maturity; <em>thalpō</em> carried the warmth of nestling — both words are used in nursing and parental care contexts. The application "just as Christ does the church" extends the metaphor to Christ as the one who feeds and warms his body. This would have resonated with the Eucharistic practices of the community: Christ literally feeds the church in the common meal.</p>',

    "30": '<p>"We are members of his body" (<em>melē esmen tou sōmatos autou</em>) invokes Paul\'s body-of-Christ ecclesiology (1 Cor 12, Eph 4:15–16). In Greek medicine (Hippocratic tradition) and philosophy, the body was understood as an integrated whole whose parts were interdependent; injury to one member affected all. Paul\'s use of this image gave early Christians a somatic, not merely organizational, understanding of their relationship to Christ and each other.</p>',

    "31": '<p>The quotation of Genesis 2:24 — "a man will leave his father and mother and be united to his wife, and the two will become one flesh" — was foundational in Jewish marriage law. The rabbis debated its implications extensively: did it prohibit polygamy (contested)? Did it establish the indissolubility of the bond? In the Dead Sea Scrolls the Damascus Document (CD 4:20–21) uses Genesis 2:24 to argue for monogamy. Jesus quotes the same verse in his teaching on divorce (Matt 19:5). Paul quotes it here in a <em>pesher</em>-style application that reaches beyond the legal question to the deeper referent revealed in Christ.</p>',

    "32": '<p>The word <em>mystērion</em> in Paul\'s usage (especially in Ephesians: 1:9; 3:3–4, 6, 9; 6:19) refers not to something mysterious or obscure but to a divine plan that was previously hidden and is now revealed — a technical sense found also in Daniel 2 (Aramaic <em>rāz</em>) and the Qumran pesher literature. The mystery here is that the "one flesh" union of Genesis 2:24 was always about Christ and the church — the human institution of marriage was a prophetic sign embedded in creation that waited for its revealed meaning. Paul is not allegorizing marriage away; he is claiming that Genesis 2:24 had a referent deeper than human marriage that Genesis itself did not yet identify.</p>',

    "33": '<p>The practical summary returns from the cosmic analogy to the household. The husband is to love, the wife to "respect" or "fear" (<em>phobētai</em>). In the ancient household code tradition, the appropriate response to a head of household was <em>phobos</em> — not terror but the respectful honor given to authority. The same root describes the children\'s relation to parents (6:1–2) and slaves\' relation to masters (6:5). Paul\'s use here is a social register word meaning appropriate deference and honor, not emotional fear. The verse deliberately mirrors the asymmetry of the preceding section: the husband\'s obligation is love (costly, self-sacrificial), the wife\'s is honor (relational, communal).</p>'
  },

  "6": {
    "1": '<p>The command for children to obey parents "in the Lord" was set against the backdrop of Roman <em>patria potestas</em> — the father\'s legal authority over the household, which in earlier Roman law included power of life and death over children (rarely exercised by Paul\'s time but culturally foundational). Greek <em>paideia</em> (education/formation) centered on learning to honor one\'s parents as the first institution of civic virtue. Jewish instruction texts (Sirach 3:1–16, Tobit 4:3–4) similarly emphasized filial obedience. Paul grounds his command in both natural law ("for this is right," <em>dikaion</em>) and the specific authority of the Lord — qualifying parental obedience by a higher loyalty.</p>',

    "2": '<p>The quotation from Exodus 20:12 (= Deut 5:16) is the Fifth Commandment, the pivot of the Decalogue between the God-directed commands (1–4) and the neighbor-directed commands (6–10). Paul\'s observation that it is "the first commandment with a promise" was a recognized point in Jewish catechesis; the rabbis noted that both honoring parents and releasing the bird\'s nest (Deut 22:6–7) carried the same promise of long life, leading to discussions about reward. The Decalogue was the foundational catechetical text for both Jewish proselytes and God-fearers who attended the synagogue — the Ephesian Gentile believers who came through synagogue contact would have known it.</p>',

    "3": '<p>The promise "that it may go well with you and that you may enjoy long life on the earth" slightly modifies the LXX, removing the specific reference to "the land which the Lord your God gives you" — a territorial promise to Israel. Paul universalizes it: "on the earth" (<em>epi tēs gēs</em>) rather than "in the land." This is a significant interpretive move: the covenant promise attached to the commandment is de-territorialized and applied to all members of the new covenant community regardless of ethnic identity. The pattern of citing the Decalogue while universalizing its application was characteristic of Hellenistic Jewish missionary preaching (cf. Philo, Josephus).</p>',

    "4": '<p>"Fathers, do not exasperate your children" (<em>mē parorgizete ta tekna hymōn</em>) directly addresses the Roman <em>patria potestas</em> tradition in which a father\'s arbitrary authority was legally protected. The corresponding verse in Colossians 3:21 adds the explanation "lest they become discouraged" — parental harshness produced the psychological damage of chronic discouragement. The command to "bring them up in the training and instruction of the Lord" (<em>paideia kai nouthesia kyriou</em>) commandeers the Greek educational vocabulary: <em>paideia</em> was the entire Greek system of moral formation through literature, music, philosophy, and practice; <em>nouthesia</em> was moral warning and correction. Paul redirects the cultural curriculum from Homeric virtue to the instruction of the Lord.</p>',

    "5": '<p>Roman slavery encompassed a wide social spectrum: educated slaves served as doctors, teachers, secretaries, and household managers alongside agricultural laborers and mine workers. Roughly a quarter to a third of the population of major cities like Ephesus were enslaved. The philosopher Epictetus was a former slave. In Paul\'s communities, slaves and free sat at the same eucharistic table — a remarkable social leveling. Paul addresses slaves as moral agents with full spiritual standing, which was itself countercultural. The phrase "masters according to the flesh" (<em>tois kata sarka kyriois</em>) implicitly relativizes their authority: this mastery is bodily and temporary, not ultimate. Christ is the true kyrios.</p>',

    "6": '<p>"Eyeservice" (<em>ophthalmodouleia</em>) appears to be Paul\'s own coinage — it is found only here and in Colossians 3:22 in ancient literature. The concept was well understood from household management discussions: Plato (Republic 3.405a) and Xenophon (Oeconomicus) discuss the difference between slaves who work diligently when watched and those who work only when supervised. The compound word crystallizes the problem: service performed only within the field of the master\'s eye. "Slaves of Christ, doing the will of God from the heart" (<em>apo psychēs</em>) — the contrast is inner motivation vs. external performance, which maps onto the entire Pauline contrast between law-observance and Spirit-led obedience.</p>',

    "7": '<p>"With good will doing service as to the Lord, and not to people" — the Stoic tradition distinguished between doing one\'s duty because it is duty (acting rightly) and doing it for external reward or fear. Paul\'s instruction has a Stoic surface but a different foundation: the good will (<em>met\' eunoias</em>) is directed toward the Lord, not grounded in the Stoic sage\'s self-sufficiency. The reorientation of one\'s work as service to Christ rather than to human authority was a profound social reframing: the slave who worked for Christ had a dignity no master could grant or remove.</p>',

    "8": '<p>The assurance that "the Lord will reward each one for whatever good they do, whether they are slave or free" invokes the final judgment as the great equalizer. In the Roman world, social status determined legal outcomes: a free person and a slave who committed the same act received different legal treatment. Paul announces that the eschatological tribunal recognizes no such distinction. The same word for "reward" (<em>komisetai</em>) was used in commercial transactions for receiving back what was owed — Paul frames divine recompense as a debt God will pay, honoring the labor that human law ignored.</p>',

    "9": '<p>"There is no favoritism with him" (<em>prosōpolēmpsia</em>, literally "face-receiving") directly subverts the patron-client system. In the Hellenistic world, favors, legal outcomes, and honor were distributed according to social status — the "face" (persona) one presented determined what one received. The Jewish tradition rejected this principle in legal proceedings (Lev 19:15; Deut 1:17; 16:19) and applied it to God (Deut 10:17; 2 Chr 19:7). Paul applies it to the master-slave relationship: the master who threatens will face the same impartial judge. The instruction to "do the same things to them" — treating slaves with the same consideration — was radical in the ancient household.</p>',

    "10": '<p>"Finally, be strong in the Lord and in his mighty power" (<em>en tō kratei tēs ischyos autou</em>) — the vocabulary of power here is drawn from the earlier prayer of 1:19 where Paul uses the same stacked power-terms to describe the resurrection power available to believers. The shift to military imagery in the following verses was natural in a world where Paul was physically chained to a Roman soldier (cf. Acts 28:16, 20). Writing from Roman imprisonment, likely around 60–62 AD, Paul had daily visual access to legionary equipment. The "strength of his might" language also echoes Isaiah 40:26, 29, where the Lord strengthens the weary.</p>',

    "11": '<p>The "whole armor of God" (<em>panoplia tou theou</em>) — the word <em>panoplia</em> (full armor set) appears in Wisdom of Solomon 5:17–20, where it describes God\'s own armor in his eschatological battle against the wicked. Paul\'s use of "of God" is deliberate: the armor is God\'s own, made available to the believer, echoing Isaiah 59:17 where the LORD himself puts on righteousness as a breastplate and a helmet of salvation. The "schemes of the devil" (<em>methodias tou diabolou</em>) — the word <em>methodeias</em> was used for cunning stratagems in military and rhetorical contexts; it implies a calculating intelligence behind the opposition.</p>',

    "12": '<p>The catalog of opponents — "rulers, authorities, powers of this dark world, spiritual forces of evil in the heavenly realms" (<em>archai, exousiai, kosmokratores tou skotous toutou, pneumatika tēs ponērias en tois epouraniois</em>) — reflects Second Temple Jewish cosmology in which the universe is populated by spiritual agents with authority over nations, cosmic domains, and human affairs. Daniel 10:13, 20 names the "prince of Persia" and "prince of Greece" as angelic powers behind earthly empires. The Qumran War Scroll envisions a final battle against these cosmic powers. Paul does not treat them as mere metaphors for human institutions; the "heavenly realms" (<em>en tois epouraniois</em>) is his specific term for the spiritual dimension that intersects with earthly reality (cf. Eph 1:3, 20; 2:6; 3:10).</p>',

    "13": '<p>"The day of evil" (<em>hēmera ponēra</em>) is an eschatological term referring to any time of crisis or testing — the Psalms speak of "the day of trouble" (Ps 20:1; 27:5), and the prophets of "the day of the LORD" as a time of judgment. Paul\'s instruction — "having done everything, to stand" (<em>hapanta katergazamenoi stēnai</em>) — reflects the ancient military ideal of holding position; in Greek tactical thinking, maintaining formation under attack was the mark of elite soldiers. "To stand" (<em>stēnai</em>) appears four times in this section (vv.11, 13, 14), suggesting it is the central image.</p>',

    "14": '<p>The armor description closely follows Isaiah 59:17: "He put on righteousness as his breastplate, and the helmet of salvation on his head." In Isaiah 59 the LORD acts because there is no human intercessor, no one righteous enough to stand in the breach. Paul now calls believers to wear this divine armor — the equipment of God himself. "Belt of truth" (<em>zōsamenoi tēn osphyn hymōn en alētheia</em>) alludes to the Roman soldier\'s belt (<em>cingulum</em>), which gathered the tunic for movement and supported the other armor. In Isaiah 11:5 the Davidic shoot has "righteousness as the belt around his waist." The "breastplate of righteousness" (<em>thōraka tēs dikaiosynēs</em>) — here <em>dikaiosynē</em> is moral integrity/covenant-faithfulness rather than forensic justification.</p>',

    "15": '<p>"Feet shod with the readiness of the gospel of peace" echoes Isaiah 52:7 — "How beautiful are the feet of those who bring good news" — the messenger racing to announce Israel\'s liberation from Babylon. The Roman soldier\'s <em>caligae</em> (hobnailed sandals) were essential for the long marches that made the legions effective; they provided grip and mobility. Paul\'s spiritual equivalent is the preparedness that comes from knowing the gospel of peace — being grounded and mobile, not paralyzed. The pairing of "gospel" and "peace" in a military context is characteristically Pauline irony: the soldier\'s weapon is the announcement of peace.</p>',

    "16": '<p>The shield here is the <em>thureos</em> — the large Roman rectangular shield (as opposed to the small round <em>aspis</em>), large enough to crouch behind and cover the entire body. Ancient incendiary weapons included arrows wrapped in tow and dipped in pitch, then lit; in siege warfare these were a feared weapon. The legions had countermeasures including soaking the <em>thureos</em> in water before battle. The "flaming arrows of the evil one" captures an image familiar to any first-century Mediterranean person who had seen military operations. Faith (<em>pistis</em>) as the shield implies that trust in God\'s promises is what intercepts the temptation before it takes hold.</p>',

    "17": '<p>The "helmet of salvation" (<em>perikephalaian tou sōtēriou</em>) is again from Isaiah 59:17 — the LORD\'s own helmet. The Roman <em>galea</em> (helmet) protected the head in close combat. Paul\'s distinction in this verse is important: for the belt, breastplate, shoes, and shield, the command is to "stand with" or "take up"; for the helmet and sword, the command shifts to "take" (<em>dexasthe</em> — receive). The helmet of salvation is received from God, not manufactured by the believer. The "sword of the Spirit, which is the word of God" — the Roman <em>gladius</em> (short sword) was for close-quarters combat; Paul identifies it as <em>rhēma</em> (the specific spoken word) rather than <em>logos</em>, suggesting the sword is the proclaimed gospel word in the moment of conflict.</p>',

    "18": '<p>Prayer bookends the armor section: the armor is put on through prayer. "Pray in the Spirit on all occasions with all kinds of prayers and requests" — the language of "all" is piled up four times (<em>dia pasēs proseuchēs... en panti kairō... en pasē proseuchē... hyper pantōn</em>), suggesting totality of orientation. "Be alert" (<em>agrypnountes</em>, literally "sleepless") recalls the watchman imagery in the OT (Isa 62:6; Ezek 3:17) and the disciples\' failure to watch in Gethsemane (Mark 14:37–38). The instruction to pray "for all the saints" reflects the early Christian understanding of the universal community as a single body whose members bear one another\'s needs before God.</p>',

    "19": '<p>Paul\'s request for prayer for "boldness" (<em>parrēsia</em>) in proclamation is historically specific: he is in Roman custody, where speaking openly about a gospel that proclaimed a crucified Jew as Lord of the empire was politically dangerous. <em>Parrēsia</em> (literally "all speech," freedom of speech) was a prized civic virtue in Athenian democracy — the right to speak freely in the assembly. In Paul\'s context it is the freedom to speak the gospel without self-censorship under pressure. The "mystery of the gospel" (<em>mystērion tou euaggeliou</em>) is the same technical term as in 3:3–6 — the previously hidden plan of God now revealed: that Gentiles are co-heirs with Israel in Christ.</p>',

    "20": '<p>"For which I am an ambassador in chains" (<em>presbeuthō en halusei</em>) is a deliberate paradox. Ambassadors (<em>presbeutai</em>) held inviolable status in the ancient world; the violation of an ambassador was casus belli. Roman, Greek, and Persian diplomatic practice all protected ambassadors from harm. Paul\'s description of himself as an "ambassador in chains" (<em>halusis</em> — the specific chain linking prisoner to guard) highlights the upended social order: the official representative of the King of kings is imprisoned by the political power that considers itself sovereign. "That I may declare it fearlessly, as I should" — Paul frames his imprisonment not as defeat but as an opportunity that requires divine courage to use rightly.</p>',

    "21": '<p>Tychicus is named in Acts 20:4 as a delegate from the province of Asia (of which Ephesus was the capital) who accompanied Paul on his collection journey to Jerusalem. He is described in the parallel passage Colossians 4:7 in nearly identical terms — "dear brother and faithful servant and fellow slave in the Lord." The near-verbatim repetition across Ephesians and Colossians supports the inference that Tychicus delivered both letters simultaneously, traveling a circuit through the Asian congregations. The role of letter-carrier in antiquity was more than postal delivery; the carrier was expected to supplement the written letter with oral explanation and news, and to vouch for the sender\'s circumstances.</p>',

    "22": '<p>The phrase "that he may encourage your hearts" (<em>parakalese tas kardias hymōn</em>) uses the Pauline word for the ministry of consolation and strengthening (the same root as <em>Paraclete</em> in John\'s Gospel). In a community anxious about Paul\'s imprisonment, Tychicus\'s visit would have served a pastoral function beyond information delivery: he embodied the network of connection that held dispersed Pauline communities together across the empire. The letter itself participated in this function — a written presence where physical presence was impossible.</p>',

    "23": '<p>The closing benediction follows the standard Hellenistic letter convention of a concluding wish for the recipients\' welfare, but with distinctively Pauline theological content. "Peace" (<em>eirēnē</em>) is the Hebrew <em>shalom</em> transliterated into Greek — comprehensive wellbeing, right relationship, wholeness, not merely the absence of conflict. "Love with faith" (<em>agapē meta pisteōs</em>) pairs the two central Christian virtues; the addition "from God the Father and the Lord Jesus Christ" makes the source explicit, locating the benediction within the Trinitarian economy of grace. The letter opened with the same double source (1:2); the closing mirrors the opening.</p>',

    "24": '<p>"Grace to all who love our Lord Jesus Christ with an undying love" — the final phrase <em>en aphtharsia</em> is striking. <em>Aphtharsia</em> means incorruption or immortality — the same word used for the resurrection body in 1 Corinthians 15:42, 50, 53–54. The closing therefore frames love for Christ in terms of resurrection permanence: a love that participates in the incorruptible life of the age to come. The plural "all" (<em>pasin</em>) suggests the letter was read in a wider circle than a single congregation — the circular letter hypothesis is supported by the absence of "in Ephesus" from several early manuscripts at 1:1. Paul closes with an inclusive address to all who share in Christ\'s undying love.</p>'
  }
}


